2 SpatialData

The SpatialData class contains 5 layers that each may hold an arbitrary number of elements. Layers are represented as follows:

  • images: list of ImageArrays
  • labels: list of LabelArrays
  • shapes: list of ShapeFrames
  • points: list of PointFrames
  • tables: list of SingleCellExperiments
dir <- file.path("extdata", "blobs")
dir <- system.file(dir, package="SpatialData")
(spd <- readSpatialData(dir))
## class: SpatialData
## images(2): blobs_image blobs_multiscale_image
## labels(2): blobs_labels blobs_multiscale_labels
## shapes(3): blobs_circles blobs_multipolygons blobs_polygons
## points(1): blobs_points
## tables(1): blobs_labels
## coords(1): global

2.1 Accession

The following accessors are currently supported:

  • image/label/shape/pointNames() to retrieve available elements of the respective layer.
  • images/labels/shapes/points() to retrieve a list of elements of the respective layer.
  • image/label/shape/point() to retrieve a single element of the respective layer.
  • $ to directly access the elements of the respective layer.

Internally, the following (more flexible) accessors are also being used:

  • element() to retrieve an element of layer e.
  • elements() to retrieve a (named, nested) list of all
    available elements, and elementNames() for their names.

SpatialData objects behave like a list, i.e., entities of a all elements can be accessed in various (equivalent) ways:

e <- "images"
i <- "blobs_image"
spd[[e]][[i]]
image(spd, i)
images(spd)[[i]]
element(spd, e, i)
elements(spd)[[e]][[i]]

2.2 Elements

The ZarrArray class is essentially an Annotated array-like object, that may contain a dense array or any type of Array (e.g., Sparse/DelayedArray). Derived here-from are the ImageArray and LabelArray classes that represent single entities of images and labels, respectively. These differ slightly in their associated metadata and array properties, but share many functions.

2.2.1 ImageArray

(ia <- image(spd))
## class: ImageArray
## channels: 0 1 2 
## axiis(cyx): 3 64 64 
## |-time(0):
## |-space(2): y x
## |-channel(1): c
## coords(1): global

2.2.2 LabelArray

(la <- label(spd))
## class: LabelArray
## axiis(yx): 64 64 
## |-time(0):
## |-space(2): y x
## |-channel(0):
## coords(1): global

2.2.3 ShapeFrame

Shapes are represented as ShapeFrames:

(sf <- shape(spd))
## class: ShapeFrame
## count: 4 
## geoms: circle 
## coords(1): global

Under the hood, this is just a DataFrame (with specialized methods and additional internal requirements), and can easily be coerced into one:

DataFrame(sf)
## DataFrame with 5 rows and 4 columns
##                     data   index  radius        type
##                  <array> <array> <array> <character>
## 1 c(36.3827739942865, ..       0       6      circle
## 2 c(32.3782919904082, ..       1       6      circle
## 3 c(24.3715882959781, ..       2       6      circle
## 4 c(18.740773348596, 2..       3       6      circle
## 5 c(46.1777953783158, ..       4       6      circle

2.2.4 PointFrame

point elements are represented as PointFrames, which are essentially pointers (i.e., they are not realized into memory until coercing to a data.frame):

(pf <- point(spd))
## class: PointFrame
## count: 200 
## data(4): x y genes instance_id
## coords(1): global
head(as.data.frame(pf))
##    x  y genes instance_id
## 1 13 44     b           9
## 2 38 29     b           7
## 3 29 47     b           3
## 4 13 40     a           9
## 5 18 14     b           4
## 6 33 52     b           5

arrow allows query operations on the underlying .parquet file in the style of dplyr, e.g.:

dplyr::filter(pf, x == y) |> select(x, y) |> as.data.frame()
##    x  y
## 1 34 34
## 2 36 36
## 3 39 39
## 4 17 17
## 5 42 42

3 Transformations

Only translation, scaling, and rotation of Image/LabelArrays are currently supported via the following functions, each of which expects a object (SD), as well as transformation data t according to:

  • translateElement(): integer vector of length 2 (row/y and col/x translation).
  • scaleElement(): numeric vector with as many elements as SD has dimensions.
  • rotateElement(): scalar integer (angle).

Available coordinate systems can be retrieved via coordNames(), and their data with coord/s(); here,

  • type: type of transformation (identity, rotate, scale, …)
  • data: transformation data (NA when type = "identity")
  • output.name the target coordinate system’s identifier
coords(ia)
##     input.axes input.name  output.axes output.name     type
## 1 c("c", "....        cyx c("c", "....      global identity

Notably, coord/s() and coordNames() will behave differently when called on a SpatialData object: only shared coordinate systems will be returned (here, there’s just one, so same thing but different…)!

coordNames(spd)
## [1] "global"

3.1 Translation

# move up'n' down
.spd <- spd
images(.spd) <- lapply(
    c(-30, 0, 30), \(t) 
    translateElement(ia, c(0, t, 0)))
lapply(
    seq_along(images(.spd)), 
    \(i) plotImage(.spd, i=i)) |>
    wrap_plots()

3.2 Rotation

# spin (anti-clockwise)
.spd <- spd
images(.spd) <- lapply(
    c(0, 30, 60), 
    \(t) rotateElement(ia, t))
lapply(
    seq_along(images(.spd)), 
    \(i) plotImage(.spd, i=i)) |>
    wrap_plots()

3.3 Scaling

# squeeze (horizontally)
.spd <- spd
images(.spd) <- lapply(
    c(1, 2/3, 1/2),
    \(t) scaleElement(ia, c(1, 1, t)))
lapply(
    seq_along(images(.spd)), 
    \(i) plotImage(.spd, i=i)) |>
    wrap_plots()

4.1 By element

Element-wise plotting is possible via plotElement, which expects a single SpatialData element as input. Images and shapes are rendered via annotation_raster; for shapes (geom_polygon), additional graphical parameters may be passed as dot (...) arguments.

ps <- list(
    p1 <- plotImage(spd), 
    p2 <- plotLabel(spd, alpha=0.5), 
    p3 <- plotShape(spd, fill="grey"))
wrap_plots(ps)

4.2 Layered

The + operator allows overlaying arbitrary layers plotted with plotImage/Label/Shape/Point. Here, argument coord specifies the target coordinate system, and will default to the first shared one available if left unspecified. Elements are internally aligned via alignElements, which in turn calls transformArray on the input image and label (type Image/LabelArray). Depending on the underlying metadata, transformElement uses scale/rotate/translateElement for transformation.

pile(ps) # or: pile(ps[[1]], ps[[2]], ps[[3]])

5 Masking

We can aggregate signals across spatial layers in various ways using mask(), which currently supports the following pairs of elements as input:

  • image by label
  • image by shape
  • label by shape
  • point by shape

In each case, a SingleCellExperiment will be obtained where rows/columns correspond to data from the 1st/2nd input element.

(sce <- mask(image(spd), label(spd)))
## class: SingleCellExperiment 
## dim: 3 786432 
## metadata(0):
## assays(1): X
## rownames(3): 0 1 2
## rowData names(0):
## colnames(786432): V1 V2 ... V786431 V786432
## colData names(3): y x instance_id
## reducedDimNames(0):
## mainExpName: NULL
## altExpNames(0):

6 Platforms

6.1 MERFISH

#devtools::load_all()
dir <- file.path("extdata", "merfish")
dir <- system.file(dir, package="SpatialData")
(spd <- readSpatialData(dir))
## class: SpatialData
## images(1): rasterized
## labels(0):
## shapes(2): anatomical cells
## points(1): single_molecule
## tables(1): cells
## coords(1): global

The dataset contains >3,000,000 points; for visualization, we here draw a random sample of 1,000:

(p <- point(spd))
## class: PointFrame
## count: 3714642 
## data(3): x y cell_type
## coords(1): global
q <- p[sample(length(p), 1e3)]
.spd <- spd; point(.spd) <- q

Underlying the following visualization is a sequential transformation, specifically, the image element undergoes a scaling and translation:

df <- coord(image(.spd))
df$transformations[[1]]
##     input.axes input.name  output.axes output.name        scale        type
## 1 c("c", "....        cyx c("c", "....      global 1, 3.863....       scale
## 2 c("c", "....        cyx c("c", "....      global              translation
##    translation
## 1             
## 2 0, 4548,....
p1 <- plotImage(.spd, width=400)
p2 <- plotShape(.spd, fill=NA, col="white")
p3 <- plotPoint(.spd, col="cell_type", size=0.5)
pile(p1, p2, p3) +
    theme(legend.key.size=unit(0.5, "lines")) +
    guides(col=guide_legend(override.aes=list(size=2)))
